description:
Skill: /mock-code-finder — silent stub via to_f64-else-passthrough.

fp-frame Series::clip_with_series (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:4727) falls back to pushing val.clone() when to_f64 fails. Scalar::to_f64 fails for Timedelta64 (returns TypeError::NonNumericValue). Result: clip_with_series on a Timedelta64 series silently passes every value through unchanged, ignoring the lower/upper bounds entirely.

Pandas clips Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 bounds element-wise:
  >>> pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('5h'), pd.Timedelta('30m')]).clip(
          lower=pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('1h'), pd.Timedelta('1h')]))
  0    0 days 05:00:00
  1    0 days 01:00:00

fp-frame returns the input unchanged.

Sister to the recently-shipped Utf8 fix (br-frankenpandas-98b6e). Same shape: when val matches a non-numeric variant, fall through to a typed branch instead of silently no-op'ing.

Fix: add a Timedelta64 branch right after the Utf8 fast path (line 4707):
  if let Scalar::Timedelta64(nanos) = val {
      if *nanos == Timedelta::NAT { out.push(val.clone()); continue; }
      let mut clipped: i64 = *nanos;
      // lower bound (if Timedelta64 and not NAT) → max
      // upper bound (if Timedelta64 and not NAT) → min
      out.push(Scalar::Timedelta64(clipped));
      continue;
  }

Tests:
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 lower bound clips to bound when below.
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 upper bound clips to bound when above.
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with NAT bound passes through unclipped (same row).
- existing numeric/Utf8 clip_with_series tests remain green.

## Finding (consistency lens, sister gap to br-0d6f8 / br-db6ec)

Series::unstack (line 6968) builds row_keys and col_keys with
Vec::contains:

  if !row_keys.contains(&row_key) {
      row_keys.push(row_key.clone());
  }
  if !col_keys.contains(&col_key) {
      col_keys.push(col_key.clone());
  }

For n entries with k unique row keys and j unique col keys:
O(n × k + n × j). For n=1M, k=j=1000: ~2×10⁹ comparisons just for
key-set construction. Same shape as br-0d6f8 (Series::drop) and
br-db6ec (DataFrame::append column union).

## Fix

HashSet for membership tracking, parallel insertion-ordered Vec
for first-seen ordering preservation:

  let mut row_keys: Vec<String> = Vec::new();
  let mut row_seen: HashSet<String> = HashSet::new();
  let mut col_keys: Vec<String> = Vec::new();
  let mut col_seen: HashSet<String> = HashSet::new();
  ...
  if row_seen.insert(row_key.clone()) {
      row_keys.push(row_key.clone());
  }
  if col_seen.insert(col_key.clone()) {
      col_keys.push(col_key.clone());
  }

Total: O(n) amortized. Insertion order preserved.

## Tests

- unstack on small composite-key Series produces expected
  rows × columns DataFrame (regression guard)
- unstack on wide input (5K entries with mix of keys) — correctness
  asserted (perf scaling implied by test size)
- existing unstack tests remain green

## Why surfaced

/modes-of-reasoning consistency lens — having fixed Series::drop
(0d6f8) and DataFrame::append (db6ec), the same Vec::contains
pattern in unstack was the natural sister. Closing the family of
hot-loop linear-scan patterns continues.

## Finding (hot-loop linear-scan pattern, sister gap to db6ec)

Series::drop (line 3572) iterates self.index labels and checks
membership in the user-provided drop list via Vec::contains:

  for (i, lbl) in self.index.labels().iter().enumerate() {
      if !labels.contains(lbl) {  // ← O(|labels|) per iteration
          new_labels.push(lbl.clone());
          new_values.push(self.column.values()[i].clone());
      }
  }

For n self-labels × m drop-labels: O(n × m). For n=1M, m=10K:
~10¹⁰ comparisons. Same shape as br-db6ec (DataFrame::append column
union) and the broader scan-and-find quadratic family.

IndexLabel derives Hash + Eq (line 86 of fp-index/src/lib.rs), so
HashSet<&IndexLabel> is a drop-in.

## Fix

  let drop_set: HashSet<&IndexLabel> = labels.iter().collect();
  for (i, lbl) in self.index.labels().iter().enumerate() {
      if !drop_set.contains(lbl) {
          new_labels.push(lbl.clone());
          new_values.push(self.column.values()[i].clone());
      }
  }

Total: O(n + m) — m to build the set, n × O(1) lookups.

## Tests

- drop with disjoint labels (no-op when label not in index)
- drop with overlapping labels removes the matching entries
- drop preserves first-occurrence ordering for non-dropped entries
- regression guard: existing drop tests remain green
- wide-input scaling test (5K labels, 500 dropped)

## Why surfaced

/deadlock-finder-and-fixer — same shape as the recently-fixed
column-union pattern (db6ec) and the scan-and-find quadratic
family (7c7d0/15f51/d8d9d/etc.). Series::drop is the natural sister
gap on labels-instead-of-columns axis.

## Finding (porting pandas Utf8 cumsum behavior)

Series::cumsum (line 5119) has Int64 + Bool specialized branches and
falls through to a Float64-only path that calls to_f64 — which errors
on Utf8.

Pandas:
  pd.Series(['a','b','c']).cumsum() → ['a', 'ab', 'abc'] (object dtype)

fp-frame: returns Err.

Sister gap to br-c4898 (cummin/cummax Utf8) — pandas defines a
'cumulative concatenate' for cumsum on strings, mirroring how
cumsum is 'cumulative add' for numbers.

## Reproducer

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      vec![0_i64.into(), 1_i64.into(), 2_i64.into()],
      vec![Scalar::Utf8("a".into()), Scalar::Utf8("b".into()),
           Scalar::Utf8("c".into())])?;
  s.cumsum();
    // before: Err (to_f64 fails on Utf8)
    // after:  Ok([Utf8("a"), Utf8("ab"), Utf8("abc")])

## Fix

Add a Utf8 branch (after the Bool branch) that accumulates
concatenated strings:

  if !values.is_empty() && values.iter().all(|v| matches!(v, Scalar::Utf8(_))) {
      let mut acc = String::new();
      let mut out = Vec::with_capacity(values.len());
      for value in values {
          if let Scalar::Utf8(s) = value {
              acc.push_str(s);
              out.push(Scalar::Utf8(acc.clone()));
          }
      }
      return Self::from_values(...);
  }

Same shape as the Int64 and Bool branches; same shape as the
cummin/cummax Utf8 fix from c4898.

## Tests

- cumsum on Utf8 concatenates: ['a','b','c'] → ['a','ab','abc']
- cumsum on Utf8 with empty strings: ['','b','c'] → ['','b','bc']
- cumsum on single-element Utf8 series: ['hello'] → ['hello']
- existing Int64/Bool/Float64 cumsum tests must remain green

## Why surfaced

/porting-to-rust applied to the recent Utf8 fix wave (c4898/83c2a/
7db78/9978d/ff284). cumsum on Utf8 is the natural completion of
the cumulative-op set.

fd90.74-123 README audit — Error Architecture table at lines 821-830. Two rows list 'LengthMismatch' as if it were a unit variant, alongside other struct-variant entries that correctly use braces:

  | IndexError | ... | OutOfBounds { position, length }, LengthMismatch, ... |
  | FrameError | ... | LengthMismatch, DuplicateIndexUnsupported, ... |

But both are struct variants:
- crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:111 — FrameError::LengthMismatch { index_len, column_len }
- crates/fp-index/src/lib.rs:1344 — IndexError::LengthMismatch { expected, actual, context }

The README has been progressively normalized (see fd90.101 for MissingIndexColumn). 'LengthMismatch' is the last remaining unit-typed-looking entry that's actually a struct variant.

Also: TypeError row shows IncompatibleDtypes { left, right } correctly with braces, so the README convention is established — the LengthMismatch entries just weren't updated.

Fix:
- IndexError row: LengthMismatch → LengthMismatch { expected, actual, context }
- FrameError row: LengthMismatch → LengthMismatch { index_len, column_len }

Pure README change.

**Severity:** MEDIUM (consistency/parity gap; backend errors leak through with backend-specific messages instead of typed client-side errors).

**Finding:** `validate_sql_identifier_length` is only called from `write_sql_with_options` (line ~6760: validates table/column/index/schema names against `conn.max_identifier_length()` before DDL). The read-path and DROP-path query builders SKIP length validation:

- `sql_select_all_query_in_schema` (line 4927) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_select_columns_query_in_schema` (line 4967) — only `validate_sql_table_name` + `validate_sql_column_name` (shape only)
- `sql_create_table_query_in_schema` (line 5031) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_insert_rows_query_in_schema` (line 5069) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_drop_table_query_in_schema` (line 5168) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `default truncate_table` (line 4216) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)

**Impact:** On a backend with `max_identifier_length` set (PG=63, MySQL=64, MSSQL=128), passing an over-cap identifier produces a SELECT/INSERT/DROP statement that the backend rejects at parse time with a backend-specific error like `identifier "..." will be truncated to 63 characters` (PG WARNING) or `Identifier name too long` (MySQL). Users see backend leakage instead of the clean typed `IoError::Sql("invalid X name '...': length N exceeds backend identifier limit (M)")` that `write_sql_with_options` produces.

**Reproducer (sketch, would need test infra):**
```rust
struct PgCap63 { /* supports_schemas=true, max_identifier_length=Some(63) */ }
let conn = PgCap63;
let long_name = "a".repeat(100);
// write_sql_with_options(&frame, &conn, &long_name, ...) → typed IoError::Sql about 63-char limit ✓
// read_sql_table(&conn, &long_name) → builds SELECT that PG rejects with raw error ✗
// sql_drop_table_query_in_schema(&conn, &long_name, None) → builds DROP that PG rejects ✗
```

**Suggested fix:** add `validate_sql_identifier_length(name, conn.max_identifier_length(), kind)` to each of the 6 query-builder functions above, mirroring what `write_sql_with_options` already does. Add a regression test in the fd90.12 quoting matrix style verifying that `sql_select_columns_query_in_schema` rejects over-cap identifiers per dialect.

**Discoverer:** cc-pandas (claude-opus-4-7) during review-mode P3 cross-review of e129119/fc4ba86/48a2f0b SQL query builders on 2026-05-02. Spotted while reviewing my own e129119 quoting matrix tests — they verify `validate_sql_identifier_length` behavior in isolation but the function isn't called by the builders themselves on the read/drop/create/insert paths.

## Finding (deadlock-finder, hot-loop linear-scan pattern)

DataFrame::value_counts (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:23771) builds
composite-key tuples per row and searches for matches via a linear
iter_mut().find():

  for i in 0..self.len() {
      // build key_parts: Vec<ScalarKey<'_>> from N columns
      if let Some((_, _, count)) = key_counts
          .iter_mut().find(|(k, _, _)| *k == key_parts)
      {
          *count += 1;
      } else {
          key_counts.push((key_parts, key_label, 1));
      }
  }

For n input rows and k unique combinations: O(n × k). For n=1M,
k=100K: ~10¹⁰ comparisons. Same shape as br-7c7d0 (Series::value_counts)
which I fixed earlier; the DataFrame variant was missed.

## Fix

Vec<ScalarKey> is Hash + Eq + PartialEq (ScalarKey derives all three),
so a HashMap<Vec<ScalarKey>, usize> index is a drop-in. Same approach
as br-7c7d0: parallel insertion-ordered Vec for first-seen-order, plus
HashMap from composite-key → index in the Vec.

  let mut key_counts: Vec<(Vec<ScalarKey>, String, i64)> = Vec::new();
  let mut idx_map: HashMap<Vec<ScalarKey<'_>>, usize> = HashMap::new();
  for i in 0..n {
      let key_parts = ...;
      match idx_map.get(&key_parts) {
          Some(&idx) => key_counts[idx].2 += 1,
          None => {
              idx_map.insert(key_parts.clone(), key_counts.len());
              key_counts.push((key_parts, label, 1));
          }
      }
  }

## Reproducer (perf, not correctness)

  let df = ... 1M rows × 3 cols, ~100K unique combinations ...;
  df.value_counts();
    // before: minutes
    // after:  <1s

## Tests

- value_counts on small DataFrame returns correct combination counts
- value_counts preserves descending sort by count (stable on ties)
- existing dataframe value_counts tests must remain green
- regression guard: 5K rows × 3 cols correctness check (perf scaling
  implied by test size)

## Why surfaced

/deadlock-finder-and-fixer applied to remaining hot-loop linear-scan
patterns. Sister gap to:
- 7c7d0 (Series::value_counts O(n²) → O(n))
- 15f51 (Series::unique/nunique)
- d8d9d (Series::duplicated/drop_duplicates)
- 5110c (Series::map/replace)
- f7201 (Series::isin)
- cec8f (Series::mode_with_dropna)
- 6ce89 (DataFrame::nunique_with_dropna)

DataFrame::value_counts is the natural completion of this pattern.

## Finding (perf lens, sister gap to br-15f51)

DataFrame::nunique_with_dropna (line 26671) iterates columns and calls
distinct_values(col.values(), dropna).len() per column:

  let values: Vec<Scalar> = self
      .column_order
      .iter()
      .map(|n| {
          let col = &self.columns[n];
          Scalar::Int64(distinct_values(col.values(), dropna).len() as i64)
      })
      .collect();

distinct_values is O(n²) (linear-scan iter().any(grouped_scalar_eq)) —
left intentionally that way to support the cross-dtype caller
DataFrame::nunique_axis1 (which pulls row-wise values from columns of
potentially different dtypes).

But this caller is iterating COLUMNS (axis=0) — each column is
homogeneous in dtype (Column::new validation), so ScalarKey-based
dedup is safe and O(n). Series::nunique_with_dropna already uses that
path (br-15f51).

For 10 cols × 1M rows × 100K unique: ~5×10¹¹ comparisons. Should be
~10M (O(N · M)).

## Reproducer (perf, not correctness)

  let df = DataFrame::new_with_column_order(
      Index::from_i64((0..1_000_000).collect()),
      // ... 10 columns of 1M int64 each, ~100K unique
  )?;
  df.nunique();
    // before: ~minutes
    // after:  <1s

## Fix

Inline the O(n) HashMap-based dedup logic per column (mirrors the
Series::nunique_with_dropna body). distinct_values stays for the
cross-dtype nunique_axis1 caller.

  let values: Vec<Scalar> = self
      .column_order
      .iter()
      .map(|n| {
          let col = &self.columns[n];
          let mut seen: HashMap<ScalarKey<'_>, ()> = HashMap::new();
          let mut missing_seen = false;
          for v in col.values() {
              if v.is_missing() {
                  if dropna { continue; }
                  missing_seen = true;
                  continue;
              }
              if let Some(key) = scalar_key_skip_missing(v) {
                  seen.insert(key, ());
              }
          }
          Scalar::Int64((seen.len() + usize::from(missing_seen)) as i64)
      })
      .collect();

## Tests

- DataFrame::nunique on a multi-column DF with mixed dtypes
  (Int64/Float64/Utf8) returns correct per-column counts
- DataFrame::nunique with nulls + dropna=false counts the null bucket
- existing dataframe nunique tests must remain green
- regression guard: scaling test (5K rows) confirms correctness without
  asserting wall time

## Why surfaced

/profiling-software-performance — sister gap to br-15f51 (Series-level
fix). Same pattern: distinct_values is fine for cross-dtype, but
single-column callers can use HashMap. DataFrame::nunique iterates
columns (each homogeneous), so it's the same single-Series shape.

## Finding (perf lens, sister gap to scan-and-find family)

Series::factorize (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:6111) maps each value
to its position in the unique-set via Vec::iter().position():

  for val in vals {
      if val.is_missing() {
          codes.push(Scalar::Int64(-1));
          continue;
      }
      let pos = uniques.iter().position(|u| u == val);
      match pos {
          Some(p) => codes.push(Scalar::Int64(p as i64)),
          None => {
              codes.push(Scalar::Int64(uniques.len() as i64));
              uniques.push(val.clone());
          }
      }
  }

For n input values with k unique: O(n × k). For n=1M, k=100K:
~10¹⁰ comparisons.

ScalarKey already derives Hash + Eq + PartialEq. Within a single
Series the values are homogeneous in dtype (Column::new validation),
so ScalarKey-based membership matches Scalar's PartialEq for in-
column pairs.

## Fix

HashMap<ScalarKey, i64> from value to its code. Parallel
insertion-ordered Vec<Scalar> for the uniques (preserves first-seen
order, matching the existing semantic).

  let mut uniques: Vec<Scalar> = Vec::new();
  let mut idx_map: HashMap<ScalarKey<'_>, i64> = HashMap::new();
  for val in vals {
      if val.is_missing() {
          codes.push(Scalar::Int64(-1));
          continue;
      }
      let key = scalar_key_allow_missing(val);
      match idx_map.get(&key) {
          Some(&p) => codes.push(Scalar::Int64(p)),
          None => {
              let code = uniques.len() as i64;
              idx_map.insert(key, code);
              uniques.push(val.clone());
              codes.push(Scalar::Int64(code));
          }
      }
  }
  drop(idx_map);

Total: O(n + k). Same shape as br-7c7d0/15f51/d8d9d/cec8f/7c962/...

## Tests

- factorize on small input produces correct (codes, uniques) pair
- factorize preserves first-seen ordering for uniques
- factorize maps repeated values to the same code
- factorize handles nulls (code = -1)
- wide-scaling test (5K values, 50 unique) confirms perf scaling

## Why surfaced

/profiling-software-performance — Vec::iter().position() in a hot
loop is the same anti-pattern fixed across the recent
scan-and-find family (7c7d0/15f51/d8d9d/db6ec/0d6f8/0528d/87bf2).

## Finding (deadlock-finder lens, hot-loop quadratic-scan pattern)

Series::value_counts (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:3576) and
Series::value_counts_with_options (line 3614) accumulate counts via:

  let mut counts: Vec<(Scalar, usize)> = Vec::new();
  for value in self.column.values() {
      if value.is_missing() { continue; }
      if let Some((_, count)) = counts
          .iter_mut()
          .find(|(existing, _)| existing.semantic_eq(value))
      {
          *count += 1;
      } else {
          counts.push((value.clone(), 1));
      }
  }

For n input values with k unique:
- Each iteration's `iter_mut().find()` scans all already-inserted entries
- Worst case (all-unique values): O(n × k) = O(n²)
- For n=1M, k=100K: ~5×10¹⁰ comparisons (catastrophic)

The pattern is the same one /deadlock-finder-and-fixer flags as
"borrow-and-iterate-with-find" (a held borrow doing linear work
inside a loop that should be O(1) per step).

## Why the O(n²) pattern instead of HashMap

The function predates / doesn't use the existing ScalarKey enum
(line 432) which already derives Hash + Eq for use as HashMap keys
in groupby. value_counts can use it directly.

## Fix

Replace the linear-scan Vec with a HashMap-keyed-by-ScalarKey index
tracker, paired with a parallel Vec<(Scalar, usize)> for first-seen
ordering preservation:

  let mut counts: Vec<(Scalar, usize)> = Vec::new();
  let mut index_map: HashMap<ScalarKey<'_>, usize> = HashMap::new();
  for value in self.column.values() {
      if value.is_missing() { continue; }
      let key = scalar_key_skip_missing(value).unwrap();
      match index_map.get(&key) {
          Some(&idx) => counts[idx].1 += 1,
          None => {
              index_map.insert(key, counts.len());
              counts.push((value.clone(), 1));
          }
      }
  }

This is O(n) amortized — each iteration is one HashMap lookup +
optional vec push. The parallel Vec preserves first-seen ordering,
which is critical because the subsequent `sort_by` is STABLE and
equal-count entries must keep their original ordering.

## Reproducer (perf, not correctness)

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      (0..1_000_000).map(|i| (i as i64).into()).collect(),
      (0..1_000_000).map(|i| Scalar::Int64(i % 100_000)).collect())?;
  s.value_counts();  // before: ~minutes. after: <1s

## Tests

- value_counts on small input still preserves first-seen ordering
  for tied counts (regression guard for the sort stability)
- value_counts on Float64 input handles NaN correctly (NaN values
  are missing and excluded)
- value_counts on string input groups equal strings
- value_counts with all-unique values returns one row per value
- Existing series_value_counts tests must remain green

## How surfaced

/deadlock-finder-and-fixer applied to "lock-held-across-loop" pattern;
the `iter_mut().find()` inside a per-element loop is the same
shape — a held borrow doing linear work inside a hot loop. Maps
cleanly to the HashMap pattern already used by groupby.

## Finding (porting pandas validation)

Sister gap to br-frankenpandas-d895b (ewm input validation):

Rolling::validate (line 8418) only checks window > 0:

  fn validate(&self) -> Result<(), FrameError> {
      if self.window == 0 {
          return Err(FrameError::CompatibilityRejected(
              "rolling window must be >= 1".to_owned(),
          ));
      }
      Ok(())
  }

But pandas also enforces min_periods <= window:

  >>> pd.Series([1,2,3]).rolling(window=3, min_periods=5).mean()
  ValueError: min_periods 5 must be <= window 3

fp-frame silently accepts. The rolling agg loop emits NaN whenever
non_null.len() < min_periods — for min_periods > window, that
condition is always true, so every output is NaN. Silent corruption
hidden behind the otherwise-plausible-looking NaN result.

## Reproducer

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      vec![0_i64.into(), 1_i64.into(), 2_i64.into()],
      vec![Scalar::Float64(1.0), Scalar::Float64(2.0), Scalar::Float64(3.0)])?;
  s.rolling(3, Some(5)).mean();
    // before: Ok([NaN, NaN, NaN]) — silent
    // after:  Err("rolling: min_periods 5 must be <= window 3")

## Fix

Extend Rolling::validate to check min_periods <= window. Same shape
as the existing window > 0 check.

  fn validate(&self) -> Result<(), FrameError> {
      if self.window == 0 { return Err(...); }
      if self.min_periods > self.window {
          return Err(FrameError::CompatibilityRejected(format!(
              "rolling: min_periods {} must be <= window {}",
              self.min_periods, self.window
          )));
      }
      Ok(())
  }

## Tests

- rolling(3, Some(5)).mean() returns Err mentioning "min_periods"
- rolling(3, Some(5)).count() / std / sum / etc. all error
- existing rolling tests with min_periods <= window remain green
- rolling(3, None) defaults min_periods=window so always valid (guard)

## Why surfaced

/porting-to-rust applied to the validation-stub family. After fixing
ewm (d895b), Rolling was the obvious sister: same shape (factory
takes user inputs, validation deferred until method invocation, but
the existing validation was incomplete).

## Finding (consistency lens)

DataFrameGroupBy::value_counts (line 32830) is the LAST instance of
the scan-and-find quadratic pattern I've been chasing across the
codebase (br-7c7d0/15f51/d8d9d/5110c/f7201/cec8f/6ce89/62849).

Per group, the function does:

  let mut val_counts: Vec<(Scalar, i64)> = Vec::new();
  for &ri in row_indices {
      let val = &col.values()[ri];
      if val.is_missing() { continue; }
      if let Some(entry) = val_counts.iter_mut().find(|(v, _)| v == val) {
          entry.1 += 1;
      } else {
          val_counts.push((val.clone(), 1));
      }
  }

For G groups × per-group n × k unique-per-group: O(G · n · k). For
1000 groups of 10K rows × 1K unique each: ~10¹⁰ comparisons.

Within a single column the values are homogeneous in dtype
(Column::new validation), so ScalarKey-based HashMap dedup is safe
and O(n) per group.

## Fix

Build a HashMap<ScalarKey, usize> per group, mirroring the parallel
insertion-ordered Vec pattern from br-7c7d0:

  let mut val_counts: Vec<(Scalar, i64)> = Vec::new();
  let mut idx_map: HashMap<ScalarKey<'_>, usize> = HashMap::new();
  for &ri in row_indices {
      let val = &col.values()[ri];
      if val.is_missing() { continue; }
      let key = scalar_key_allow_missing(val);
      match idx_map.get(&key) {
          Some(&idx) => val_counts[idx].1 += 1,
          None => {
              idx_map.insert(key, val_counts.len());
              val_counts.push((val.clone(), 1));
          }
      }
  }
  drop(idx_map);

Subsequent sort_by_key by count descending is preserved (stable
sort). First-seen ordering for tied counts preserved by the parallel
Vec.

## Tests

- DataFrameGroupBy::value_counts on a 2-group small DF returns
  correct (group, value) → count rows
