## Finding (porting pandas Utf8 cummax/cummin behavior)

Series::cummin (line 5163) and cummax (line 5207) have specialized
branches for Int64 and Bool, then fall through to a Float64-only
path:

  let v = val.to_f64().map_err(ColumnError::from)?;

For Utf8 input, to_f64() fails → returns Err. But pandas supports
string cumulative max/min lexicographically:

  >>> pd.Series(['b','a','c']).cummax()
  0    b
  1    b
  2    c
  dtype: object
  >>> pd.Series(['b','a','c']).cummin()
  0    b
  1    a
  2    a

Sister gap to br-frankenpandas-526a2 (is_monotonic_increasing).
The to_f64 fallback was the same kind of stub that breaks on
non-numeric input.

## Reproducer

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      vec![0_i64.into(), 1_i64.into(), 2_i64.into()],
      vec![Scalar::Utf8("b".into()), Scalar::Utf8("a".into()),
           Scalar::Utf8("c".into())])?;
  s.cummax();
    // before: Err (to_f64 fails on Utf8)
    // after: Ok([Utf8("b"), Utf8("b"), Utf8("c")])

## Fix

Add a Utf8 branch (after the Int64 and Bool branches) that scans
strings lexicographically:

  if !values.is_empty() && values.iter().all(|v| matches!(v, Scalar::Utf8(_))) {
      let mut acc: Option<&str> = None;
      let mut out = Vec::with_capacity(values.len());
      for value in values {
          if let Scalar::Utf8(s) = value {
              acc = match acc {
                  None => Some(s.as_str()),
                  Some(a) => Some(if a > s.as_str() { a } else { s.as_str() }),
              };
              out.push(Scalar::Utf8(acc.unwrap().to_string()));
          }
      }
      return Self::from_values(...);
  }

cummin uses `<` instead of `>`. The existing dtype check
(values.iter().all(matches!(Utf8))) is the same pattern as the
Int64 and Bool branches.

