## Finding (consistency lens, sister gap to br-9978d nlargest/nsmallest Utf8 fix)

Series::rank_with_pct (line 7803) extracts f64 keys per value; for
Utf8 input, val.to_f64() returns Err and the value is pushed to
null_positions:

  for (i, v) in vals.iter().enumerate() {
      if v.is_missing() {
          null_positions.push(i);
      } else if let Ok(f) = v.to_f64() {
          sortable.push((i, f));
      } else {
          null_positions.push(i);  // ← Utf8 silently treated as null
      }
  }

For all-Utf8 input, every value lands in null_positions. The result
depends on na_option:
- "keep" (default) → all NaN (silent data loss; no Err)
- "top" → all rank 1 (everyone tied for first)
- "bottom" → all rank n (everyone tied for last)

Pandas ranks strings lexicographically:
  pd.Series(['c', 'a', 'b']).rank() → [3.0, 1.0, 2.0]

fp-frame: returns all-NaN (na_option='keep' default).

## Reproducer

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      vec![0_i64.into(), 1_i64.into(), 2_i64.into()],
      vec![Scalar::Utf8("c".into()), Scalar::Utf8("a".into()),
           Scalar::Utf8("b".into())])?;
  s.rank("average", true, "keep").unwrap();
    // before: [NaN, NaN, NaN]
    // after:  [Float64(3.0), Float64(1.0), Float64(2.0)]

## Fix

Reuse rank_numeric_positions by converting each Utf8 value to a
canonical f64 key derived from sorted-unique-string order:

  if matches!(self.column().dtype(), DType::Utf8) {
      let mut unique_strings: Vec<&str> = ...sorted, deduped...;
      let key_map: HashMap<&str, f64> = unique_strings.iter().enumerate()
          .map(|(rank, s)| (*s, rank as f64))
          .collect();
      // Build sortable Vec<(idx, f64)> using the map.
      // Pass to rank_numeric_positions.
  }

Equal strings → equal f64 keys → same rank for ties (preserves
method='average'/'min'/'max'/'dense' tie semantics). Sort order in
ascending=true path matches the lex order, since unique-string
indices are assigned in lex order.

